Some observations, maybe it helps somebody to fix the issue:

### Setting locale

[Adding](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/pull/19245/files#diff-00b29588edfbcf3aeb68a4bcdc4278543f755fa428ae8194a280436386f8654fR439) `std::setlocale(LC_ALL, "en_US.UTF-8");` makes the test pass.

### Original test

```cpp
BOOST_AUTO_TEST_CASE(unicodepath)
{
    // Attempt to create a database with a UTF8 character in the path.
    // On Windows this test will fail if the directory is created using
    // the ANSI CreateDirectoryA call and the code page isn't UTF8.
    // It will succeed if created with CreateDirectoryW.
    fs::path ph = m_args.GetDataDirBase() / "test_runner_â¿_ð_20191128_104644";
    CDBWrapper dbw(ph, (1 << 20));

    fs::path lockPath = ph / "LOCK";
    BOOST_CHECK(fs::exists(lockPath));
}
```

My Visual Studio debugger shows that path `fs::path ph = m_args.GetDataDirBase() / "test_runner_â¿_ð_20191128_104644";` is garbled once created. Likely `"test_runner_â¿_ð_20191128_104644"` is intepreted using some some local codepage.

### Modified test with euro sign

(No pun intended :))

```cpp
BOOST_AUTO_TEST_CASE(unicodepath)
{
    // Attempt to create a database with a UTF8 character in the path.
    // On Windows this test will fail if the directory is created using
    // the ANSI CreateDirectoryA call and the code page isn't UTF8.
    // It will succeed if created with CreateDirectoryW.
    // fs::path ph = m_args.GetDataDirBase() / "test_runner_â¿_ð_20191128_104644"; // REMOVED
    fs::path ph = m_args.GetDataDirBase() / L"test_runner_â¬_20191128_104644"; // ADDED
    CDBWrapper dbw(ph, (1 << 20));

    fs::path lockPath = ph / "LOCK";
    BOOST_CHECK(fs::exists(lockPath));
}
```

This test leads on my computer to creating of two folders in `C:\Users\kimi\AppData\Local\Temp\test_common_Bitcoin Core\efd602083fe69783d5e6eff1220a12770bd2168d338ae233e260bae6a10c6068`:

* `test_runner_ï¿½_20191128_104644`
* `test_runner_â¬_20191128_104644`

`â¬` was used because it can be represented by two bytes.

Note that using `L"test_runner_â¿_ð_20191128_104644"` leads to `class std::system_error: No mapping for the Unicode character exists in the target multi-byte code page.` error which seems to make sense to me.

